<TEXT>
wildfires sunday threatened centuriesold 
giant sequoia trees in the states midsection and crackled toward 
homes along the mountain ridges surrounding los angeles 
the fires erupted during another california fall heat wave with 
temperatures nudging 100 degrees in many areas and santa ana winds 
dried and heated by inland deserts reaching 30 mph 
more than 3500 acres were blackened in the fires several of 
them mancaused authorities said a windpushed 2000acre blaze 
in the angeles national forest endangered homes in the path of the 
flames 30 miles north of los angeles 
the fires huge brown smoke plume rising 7000 feet skyward 
could be seen 50 miles away at los angeles international airport 
mountain residents of the northeast san fernando valley were put 
on alert but no evacuations were ordered about 200 firefighters 
were battling the blaze and hundreds more were on the way late in 
the afternoon 
this one is giving us real problems said us forest 
service spokesman bruce bundick its going in about three 
different directions faster than we can corral it 
about 160 miles northwest firefighters battling a 600acre fire 
in sequoia national park were optimistic a buffer zone cleared in a 
previous controlled burn would save the magnificent trees in the 
3squaremile giant forest said park spokesman bill tweed 
the ancient trees are considered the largest living things on 
earth 
these are certainly one of the biological wonders of the 
world tweed said the fire will inevitably reach the edge of 
the giant forest we think that because of the steps taken we can 
prevent it from going into the forest 
about 100 campers fled the flames which started at 8 am in 
potwisha camp ground about 30 miles northeast of visalia a 
careless camper or angler was the suspected cause of the blaze 
tweed said 
another fire 85 miles southeast of los angeles in riverside 
county charred 800 acres near hemet but firefighters were gaining 
the upper hand and containment was anticipated by dawn monday said 
joanne evans a spokeswoman for the california department of 
forestry 
two smaller fires erupted in the mountainous eastern portion of 
the angeles national forest one started by children playing with 
matches and a cigarette lighter destroyed a house 
</TEXT>
