<TEXT>
republican sen john h chafee admits 
some people may find it ironic that richard a licht is challenging 
him in his run for a third senate term 
the democratic licht rhode islands lieutenant governor was 20 
years old when his uncle frank licht defeated chafee in his 1968 
bid for a third term as governor 
and licht who hasnt lost an election in his 13 years as a 
politician said he has no intention of starting now 
but chafee 64 who narrowly won a second senate term in 1982 
against former attorney general julius c michaelson with 51 
percent of the vote said he feels confident as the nov 8 election 
approaches 
you can never be totally sure as a candidate but you can tell 
some things and certainly i think the people appreciate what ive 
done for them over the years chafee said recently 
chafee the first rhode island republican to be elected to the 
senate is considered a moderate and there are few substantial 
issues separating the two men 
earlier this year chafee announced support for a national 
parental leave bill a measure backed by licht in the rhode island 
general assembly 
both of the candidates also support open space preservation 
chafee who has been endorsed by four major national environmental 
organizations said he would work to initiate a 10 billion federal 
open space program if reelected 
licht sponsored several bills last year that led to the states 
65 million openspace bond issue chafee has charged that the idea 
was first his 
as the election draws near the candidates have turned to 
attacks and the resulting barrage of television commercials has 
pushed their campaign spending to nearly 25 million each 
chafee ran a television ad asserting that when licht represented 
the east side of providence in the state senate from 1975 to 1984 
he missed one out of every three votes 
did he not care was he afraid to take a stand the ad asks 
or was he too busy doing something else 
licht in turn ran two ads that said he has had a 90 percent 
attendance record in the past six years he said he missed a number 
of votes in the early 1980s because of his fathers fatal illness 
and his own role in a lawsuit that overturned a controversial 1982 
redistricting plan 
another licht ad attacked chafee for his voting record on issues 
concerning senior citizens a familiar democratic tactic 
nationwide 
chafee voted 12 times to cut social security and five times to 
cut medicare said licht who has been endorsed by the national 
council of senior citizens 
polls continue to show chafee in the lead although licht has 
narrowed the gap slightly a poll taken in september gave chafee a 
lead of 30 percentage points over the democrat with 59 percent of 
the vote a poll taken in early october with the same 5 percentage 
point margin of error showed chafee with 54 percent of the vote 
while licht was the choice of 33 percent of the 400 people surveyed 
