<TEXT>
researchers say southern poultry farmers could 
save an estimated 7 million a year by using softer lowerpower 
lights in their broiler houses 
high summer heat makes chickens go off their feed so producers 
keep broiler houses lighted during the summer nights so the birds 
will eat during the cooler hours says james w deaton of the 
departments agricultural research service 
deaton said farmers traditionally use 75 or 100watt bulbs 
because they want to simulate actual daylight 
but our tests show that broiler chickens more than two weeks 
old eat normally and gain just as much weight under 25watt 
bulbs he said in a report released here by the agency 
deaton who works at the departments south central poultry 
research laboratory in mississippi said the annual savings could 
amount to 7 million across the south or about 1000 for a 
typical producer who raises about 160000 chickens during the 
summer 
the tests also showed that chickens under the dimmer lights 
waste less feed energy in fighting running around and 
chirping he said 
