<TEXT>
associated press writer 
washington ap the supreme court today agreed to consider 
allowing states to give larger retirement benefits to public 
employees forced to quit work before age 60 
the court said it will review a ruling that struck down an ohio 
pension law provision on grounds it violated a federal law against 
discrimination based on age 
the ohio provision was challenged by june betts a former speech 
pathologist for the hamilton county mental retardation department 
when her work degenerated because of medical problems ms betts 
was given a choice by the state in 1985 of taking unpaid medical 
leave or retirement with a standard pension 
she was barred from receiving more generous disability 
retirement benefits because she was 61 
a provision of the state pension plan allowed disability 
benefits only for those who worked for the state for at least five 
years and were under 60 when forced to quit 
ms betts pension would have been 15850 a month under the 
standard plan compared to 355 a month in disability retirement 
benefits 
the 6th us circuit court of appeals last june upheld a federal 
judges ruling in ms betts favor that threw out the states 
agebased pension provision 
the appeals court said the provision violated the federal age 
discrimination in employment act 
the appeals court said the federal law permits agebased 
benefits only when they can be justified by a substantial 
business purpose 
ohio officials failed to prove that giving larger benefits to 
younger workers is justified by cost considerations the appeals 
court said 
in fact the appeals court said such an arrangement might prove 
more costly to the state since a worker who becomes disabled at a 
younger age would draw more in benefits over the course of the 
workers lifetime than someone disabled at 60 or older 
ohio officials argued that the states agebased provision is 
permissible because it was adopted prior to enactment of the 
federal age discrimination in employment act the state said 
federal appeals courts other than the 6th circuit have agreed with 
its position 
the case is public employees retirement system of ohio vs 
betts 88389 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

