<TEXT>
a group of us physicians that toured 
kurdish refugee camps has concluded iraq used chemical weapons 
against the ethnic kurdish minority in northern iraq a spokesman 
said 
dr robert mullan cookdeegan representing the bostonbased 
physicians for human rights said iraq most likely used a high 
dose of one of the kind of irritant agents or a nerve agent he 
did not elaborate 
the physician also accused turkey of covering up iraqs use of 
chemical weapons for security and economic reasons 
turkey wants to keep good relations with iraq and win a role in 
rebuilding the nation after its 8year war with iran 
a turkish government report maintains no traces of poison gas 
were found on the refugees during medical screenings but turkish 
officials have said their report does not eliminate the possibility 
that iraq used such weapons 
cookdeegan said the groups findings were based on interviews 
with more than 100 kurds who fled into turkey and also on medical 
questionnaires given to 25 refugees 
the doctor a senior associate working for the office of 
technology assessment at the us congress spoke to the associated 
press in an interview thursday on condition the information be used 
sunday after the threemember delegation left turkey 
the teams other two members were dr howaro hu from the harvard 
school of public health and asfandiar shukri a detroitbased 
physician 
about 60000 kurds fled to turkey in august claiming iraq 
dropped chemical bombs on their settlements they now live in five 
tent cities in southeastern turkey 
it is difficult to explain the sudden exodus of people that 
were used to being shot at if it would have been a conventional 
weapon attack there would have been evidence of physical injuries 
such as bullet wounds cookdeegan said 
iraq used chemical weapons particularly on a population within 
its border he said 
he said the kurdish refugees most commonly complained about 
bloody diarrhea vomiting skin irritation and eye and respiratory 
problems 
those are very typical symptoms of chemical agents called 
irritants cookdeegan said 
he added that the refugees also described small animals such as 
birds and bees dying right after the attack 
cookdeegan criticized the turkish government for witholding 
information about the issue 
he said the turkish government also did not release the results 
of autopsy reports on kurdish refugees who died immediately after 
arriving in turkey 
the turkish government announced a month ago that it would turn 
down any efforts to send un experts into turkey to determine if 
iraq used poison gas against kurds 
the 14page questionnaire used by the threemember team 
contained dozens of queries requiring detailed answers about the 
respondents health before and after the attack 
cookdeegan said they will analyze the questionnaires and 
prepare a report in a month 
investigators for the us senate foreign relations committee 
also reported after touring the refugee camps in turkey that iraq 
used chemical weapons in attacks to depopulate iraqs kurdish 
regions 
we find no question that iraqs policy in kurdistan has the 
characteristics of genocide the two staff members peter w 
galbraith and christopher von hollen jr concluded in a report to 
the foreign relations commitee chairman claiborne pell dri 
last month 
the kurds 20 million people living in a region that lies in 
turkey iran and iraq have been fighting battles for independence 
for the past century 
the latest rebellion took advantage of iraqs war with iran 
soon after an aug 20 ceasefire went into effect in that war 
iraq turned upon the kurds unleashing warhardened elite troops 
upon the kurdish guerrillas 
</TEXT>
