<TEXT>
scholars say few people would have been more 
surprised by the pledge of allegiances prominence in the 1988 
presidential campaign than the man who wrote it he was a socialist 
the pledge first appeared in a boston magazine the youths 
companion 96 years ago on sept 8 1892 
although there are competing claims to authorship most 
authorities credit the rev francis bellamy a baptist minister who 
preached against big business and served as vice president of the 
society of christian socialists 
his daughterinlaw rachel bellamy 92 of rochester ny 
recalls him as tall proud and kind of stuffy she said he 
eventually left the ministry because he felt the church was not 
doing enough to help the working man 
louise harris of providence ri who has written two books on 
the history of the pledge believes bellamys congregation grew 
tired of his political homilies one was entitled jesus the 
socialist and forced him out of the pulpit 
in any event bellamy joined the staff of the youths companion 
in 1891 and apparently composed the pledge a few months later 
while the magazine was in the midst of a campaign to sell american 
flags 
the youths companion had pioneered the sale of subscription 
premiums ranging from school uniforms to silver tea services 
but it achieved its greatest commercial success and its enduring 
legacy with its drive to put a flag in every school in the land 
the flags were priced at 330 to 13 depending on size to 
help schools raise the money the magazine provided flag 
certificates that pupils could sell for 10 cents apiece 
starting a year early the youths companion urged school 
children to prepare to celebrate the 400th anniversary of columbus 
voyage to america which was coming up in october 1892 
to show it was truly companionable the magazine even published 
a suggested columbian celebration ceremony most of it just 
happened to require a flag 
sandwiched between a presidential proclamation and an ode to 
columbus both long forgotten was the original 23word pledge 
memorable both for its sentiment and its economy of phrasing i 
pledge allegiance to my flag and to the republic for which it 
stands one nation indivisible with liberty and justice for all 
it was not until 1923 that the words my flag were replaced 
by the flag of the united states of america out of concern that 
immigrant children might otherwise think they were pledging 
allegiance to some other flag 
the phrase under god was inserted in 1954 at the behest of 
president eisenhower who said that in this way we shall 
constantly strengthen those spiritual weapons which forever will be 
our countrys most powerful resource in peace and war 
the original version of the pledge was not signed but once it 
had caught on in the schools rival claims to authorship quickly 
emerged one group pushed for james b upham an editor of the 
youths companion the other favored bellamy 
harris and a few other scholars argue that upham was the author 
but two formal investigations one conducted by the us flag 
association in 1939 and the other by the library of congress in 
1957 concluded that bellamy was responsible 
david whitman a researcher in washington dc says bellamy 
espoused a relatively benign form of socialism 
the nationalist movement which he belonged to wanted to 
nationalize chunks of the american economy but have them controlled 
at the municipal level he did not practice or preach violent 
overthrow of the government by any means whitman said 
controversy over the pledge erupted in the 1940s when jehovahs 
witnesses refused to recite it in the public schools members of 
the sect said swearing allegiance to a material object violated 
their religious principles which dictated allegiance only to god 
the supreme court initially rejected such arguments ruling in a 
1940 case that public schools could expel children who did not 
recite the pledge the court reversed itself in 1943 and said 
children could not be compelled to recite the pledge 
meantime jehovahs witnesses had been subjected to vicious 
attacks in dozens of communities in richwood va for example 
members of the sheriffs department and american legion forced 
seven members of the sect to drink large quantities of castor oil 
then tied them together and paraded them through the town 
bellamy was an avid fan of saying the pledge said whitman 
but i cant imagine how he would have felt about it if he had 
lived to see the mob violence of the 40s 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

