<TEXT>
business inventories continued their steady 
rise in august the government said monday but economists remain 
untroubled because the expansion is not outpacing strong sales 
the commerce department said goods held on shelves and backlots 
rose 08 percent to 7337 billion following a 07 percent gain in 
july it was the 20th consecutive monthly increase 
rising inventories can be a sign of economic sluggishness as 
manufacturers order production cuts and layoffs while goods in 
reserve are sold off 
however analysts are not particularly troubled by current 
inventory levels because sales also have been strong compared with 
a year ago inventories are up 87 percent while sales are up 80 
percent 
the department said august sales totaled 4877 billion up a 
brisk 11 percent from july when the gain was a slight 01 
percent it was the ninth increase in a row 
if were looking for a reason for a slowdown in 1989 it wont 
be excess inventory building typically recessions develop when 
there are excess levels of inventory and were not looking at those 
levels this year said john hagens an economist with the wefa 
group a bala cynwyd pa forecasting firm 
inventory accumulation in august was led by a 14 percent rise 
at retailers where sales are the slowest wholesale inventories 
were up 06 percent while inventories at factories where an export 
boom has kept sales strongest increased 05 percent 
however half of the inventory buildup among retailers is 
accounted for by a 29 percent rise at auto dealers car sales have 
been strong this year so dealers did not offer price cuts or 
financing incentives to move cars from the old model year off their 
lots 
inventories are in pretty good shape with the notable 
exception of apparel said maury n harris an economist with 
painewebber inc however the overall inventory level wont 
remain in good shape unless retail sales pick up in october and 
november but i think they will 
in sales a 21 percent increase at manufacturing plants more 
than offset a 01 percent decline at the retail level wholesalers 
reported a 07 percent increase 
an advance estimate of retail sales for september released last 
week showed a 04 percent decline 
the combination of moderately strong gain in inventories and an 
even more robust sales increase left the inventorytosales ratio 
at 150 unchanged from july and june and up slightly from 149 a 
year ago that means it would take 15 months to exhaust 
inventories at the august sales pace a ratio not considered 
unusually high 
</TEXT>
