<TEXT>
a space shuttle main rocket engine will 
be testfired wednesday at the marshall space flight center the 
first extended firing since the roar of saturn rockets echoed 
across huntsville in the 1960s 
its going to be something huntsville hasnt heard for quite 
awhile marshall spokesman dom amatore said 
the 15second firing is part of a series of tests on the shuttle 
main engines and coincides with the citys space awareness week 
nasa engineers want to determine how long the rocket motors 
fueled by hydrogen and oxygen from the shuttles huge external 
tank can run if needed the engines now operate for about eight 
minutes during a shuttle launch 
shuttle engine no 0208 installed in the test stand in august 
was warmed up in a 15second start test last month 
after this weeks test a third test firing of 45 seconds will 
be scheduled in november amatore said the primary goal of the 
first brief tests is to verify that marshall can handle the firings 
and whether a metal flame bucket on the test stand can handle 
the rocket exhaust 
the last test firing of a big rocket motor at marshall was a 
saturn test on sept 11 1969 about two months after men first set 
foot on the moon 
marshall is nasas main propulsion center in addition to 
developing the saturn rockets it manages space shuttle propulsion 
systems including the main engines and solid fuel booster rockets 
which are testfired in utah 
space awareness week includes a visit by the crew of the 
shuttle discovery 
the five astronaunts who flew last month in the first 
postchallenger shuttle mission are to be in huntsville on thursday 
and friday to thank marshall engineers 
they also will lead a parade and appear at a public reception 
thursday 
on wednesday singer john denver and former new mexico senator 
and apollo astronaut harrison schmitt will be in town to discuss 
proposed new space missions 
denver who hopes to ride into orbit with a soviet crew in 1990 
will talk about earth observation missions while schmitt will 
discuss proposals for manned missions to the moon and mars 
</TEXT>
