barr said the timing of the indictment has nothing whatsoever 
to do with politics or swindalls request to be indicted 
swindall was first linked publicly to the money laundering 
investigation earlier this year when it was disclosed that his aug 
28 1987 meeting with an undercover federal agent posing as a 
money launderer for underworld figures had been videotaped 
money laundering is a term for various methods of getting 
around federal currency laws by transferring illicitly raised cash 
drug money for example into bank accounts in such a way that 
its origin is hid 
swindall was introduced to the undercover agent by charles 
lechasney a former atlanta businessman who was active in 
republican circles lechasney is one of the two men scheduled to go 
on trial next week on moneylaundering charges 
lechasney and several swindall aides testified before the grand 
jury last month swindall testified before the grand jury in 
february 
in june atlanta newspapers obtained several tape recordings 
from the investigation and published excerpts from a series of 
conversations between swindall lechasney and the undercover agent 
the tapes showed that swindall continued to pursue negotiations 
for an 850000 home construction loan after being told it might be 
financed with drug money he would be helping to launder 
swindall was quoted on the tapes as saying that the source of 
the money was charles problem since lechasney would be 
obtaining the money to lend to swindall he added i frankly 
dont think its incumbent upon me to go out and find out where xyz 
corp gets their money or for that matter where chrysler corp 
gets their money if they set back the odometer thats their 
problem 
he ended the negotiations after being told he would have to 
accept the money in person in cash and sign a receipt 
swindall later apologized for his role in the negotiations 
calling it a mistake in judgment but he denied any wrongdoing 
he also asked the house ethics committee to determine if he had 
violated any law or house rule the panel agreed to investigate 
but has not issued a ruling 
the indictment said swindall lied when he told the grand jury 
last february that he did not have any concrete indication that 
lechasney and the undercover agent were discussing illegal 
activities 
swindall testified that he was suspicious of the agent but did 
not have enough information to report the matter to authorities 
the indictment said 
another count of the indictment accuses swindall of lying when 
he denied the agent discussed keeping the large cash loan from 
being reported to federal regulators 
