<TEXT>
a researcher experimenting with a new 
more sensitive test for the aids virus said monday that the virus 
does not appear to be carried in sperm cells 
that discovery could eventually mean that men with aids could 
father children by separating their sperm cells from infected semen 
and using those cells for artificial insemination 
semen which is ejaculated is made up of both sperm cells and 
seminal fluid 
but dr bernard poisez a researcher at the state university of 
new york health science center at syracuse said its a discovery 
that needs more study 
all were saying is that we have a test thats so good we can 
detect these things and now we need to do some very carefully 
conducted clinical tests poisez said 
he said he wouldnt recommend that men infected with aids 
attempt to pursue fatherhood through artificial insemination and he 
doesnt think fertility clinics or in vitro centers would agree to 
try this without further testing 
poisez said determining whether the aids virus is carried inside 
a sperm cell is one of many studies to exploit a new means of 
testing for the aids virus 
the new technique developed by cetus corp of emeryville 
calif uses a chemical reaction called a polymerase chain 
reaction to amplify genetic material such as that from the aids 
virus a million times making it easier to detect poisez said 
the test is faster more accurate and cheaper than some current 
aids tests 
another finding with the new test poisez said is a decline in 
the number of men with aids who have the virus in their semen 
other researchers using the test have documented similar findings 
he said 
poisez said he has looked at 500 semen samples over the past 
four or five years and that over that period even with a more 
sensitive test the number of samples containing the virus has 
fallen 
initially about 75 percent of the men had the virus in their 
semen but recently poisez said researchers have found the virus in 
just 20 percent of homosexual men who had similar characteristics 
as the initial group 
we think this is because they have fewer white blood cells in 
their semen said poisez as a result of safe sex and better 
care we believe the amount of infections and level of inflammation 
has been reduced 
without the infections and inflammations the number of white 
blood cells decreases poisez said 
this is another finding that needs to be studied but poisez 
said it could eventually mean that researchers could determine when 
its especially dangerous to have even safe sex 
he said researchers at the state health center are currently 
studying whether the test can be used to determine 
how effective about six or seven aidsfighting drugs are by 
measuring how quickly they are reducing the number of aidsinfected 
cells in the body 
whether some mothers infected with aids would be better 
candidates for prenatal use of aidsfighting drugs 
if there are particular times when its more likely for an 
unusually large number of aidsinfected cells to be present in the 
semen 
