<TEXT>
the us bases agreement with the philippines 
for the first time explicitly bans american soldiers and sailors 
who test positive for aids from serving in another country 
state department officials said monday it was the first time 
such a provision was included in a bases agreement it also may 
ease a dispute with manila over reported cases of the infectious 
disease among bar hostesses 
pentagon policy since january 1987 has barred overseas 
assignments for service personnel who test positive for acquired 
immune deficiency syndrome aids testing of recruits began in 
october 1986 
soldiers or sailors with aids may remain in the service within 
the united states unless and until they show symptoms of the 
disease at that point they are honorably discharged 
under a section of the bases agreement dealing with aids as a 
social issue 
the two governments affirmed their common concern over the 
global problem of aids and their common interest in the 
prevention and control of this disease 
the two governments agreed to exchange releasable 
information on the incidence of the infection 
the us government pledged that us military personnel who 
tested positive would not be assigned abroad 
the two governments agreed to have a committee look into ways 
to cooperate in prevention education testing detection and 
control 
