<TEXT>
increases in poverty rates and income 
stagnation among blacks have helped push the economic gap between 
black and white families below figures from the late 1970s and 
1960s a private research organization said monday 
a study by the liberaloriented center on budget and policy 
priorities concluded that both black married and singleparent 
families lost economic ground behind white families during the last 
decade 
in 1987 the income of the typical black family at 18098 
equaled just 561 percent of the typical white familys income 
32274 a lower percentage than any year in the late 1970s or 
late 1960s 592 percent center director robert greenstein said 
in a statement 
median family income for black families decreased by 854 
between 1978 and 1987 while the median income for white families 
increased 276 the study said 
greenstein said the center which studies government spending 
and public policy issues as they affect low and moderateincome 
americans used 1978 as a comparison year because economic 
conditions such as overall unemployment rates 62 percent in 
1978 were similar to those of 1987 61 percent 
black unemployment has dropped significantly in recent years 
but this has not been matched by comparable increases in black 
family income and declines in black poverty he said 
the evidence indicates that declines in wages for black 
workers compared to the 1970s and budget cuts at both federal and 
state levels in programs for lowincome families have contributed 
to black economic slippage greenstein said 
the study said that after adjusting for inflation the typical 
black fulltime black worker earned 315 a week in 1987 figure 
lower than that in any year in the 1970s when the wages ranged from 
340 to 330 this is compared to the 1987 salary given to their 
white counterparts whose salary ranged hovered around 420 
throughout the 1970s 
regionally income disparities between black and white families 
have increased since the late 1970s everywhere except in the west 
the study said the gap widened most in the midwest where typical 
black family income was nearly 4700 lower in 1987 than in the 
late 1970s while the income of the typical white family was only 
700 below the late1970s figures 
the most recent figures for 1987 indicate that black median 
family income was 634 percent of white income in the west 586 
percent in the northeast 563 percent in the south and 521 
percent in the midwest 
the study noted the growing income disparity between blacks and 
whites is a result of the growing income gap between upper and 
lowerincome families in the nation as a whole 
in 1987 the gap reached its widest point in 40 years it 
said as the poorest twofifths of american families received 
154 percent of the national family income in both 1986 and 1987 
their lowest share since the census bureau first collected data in 
1947 
conversely the richest onefifth of all families received 437 
percent of the national family income in 1986 and 1987 the highest 
percentage on record it said 
other findings included 
poverty rates for both blacks and whites climbed above levels 
in the 1970s with 2 million more blacks and 8 million more 
americans overall living in poverty in 1987 than in 1978 
despite a fifth year of economic recovery the black poverty 
rate rose from 311 percent in 1986 to 331 percent in 1987 while 
the white poverty rate declined from 11 percent to 105 percent 
budget reductions in programs for lowincome households has 
disproportionately affected blacks who are three times more likely 
than whites to be poor 
