sad and shameful 
the nonserbs fear milosevic seeks to boost his national power 
and that of serbia yugoslavias largest republic 
milosevic assured them serbia has no claims to the territory 
of other republics it does have claim to territory in its own 
republic 
vojvodina and kosovo are historically part of serbia 
his speech indicated that rifts that opened up in clashes last 
week with suvar and party chief milan kucan of liberal northern 
slovenia still divide yugoslavias three most important communist 
leaders 
suvar a croat advocated a fundamental renewal of socialism 
and urgent economic and political reforms to solve mounting foreign 
debt and stagnation 
kucan later expressed unreserved support for suvars speech 
milosevic made plain he wants the problem of control over kosovo 
sorted out before economic reform goes ahead 
the meeting was billed as a historic gathering to shake up the 
party leadership 
all the incompetent and compromised people must go and this 
society must be ensured of a perspective suvar said monday 
but no immediate word surfaced on any sweeping personnel changes 
azem vlasi the top ethnic albanian leader from kosovo rejected 
serbian calls to step down 
to date four members of the 23man politburo have said they 
will resign their resignations are expected to be formally 
accepted by the 162member central committee on tuesday 
suvar said last week up to onethird of the central committee 
could be replaced 
few leaders who spoke monday offered any new suggestions to 
solve yugoslavias woes 
kucan however advanced the novel idea of a referendum to test 
the partys popularity in slovenia and denied that the republics 
liberal leadership has no popular support 
the party chief of the republic of montenegro marko orlandic 
attacked the federal government of premier branko mikulic and 
blamed it for for failing to solve the economic crisis 
suvar advocated expanded private ownership increased foreign 
investment and the shutdown of unprofitable state enterprises he 
said key managerial positions limited to communists might be opened 
to nonparty members 
suvar also said a new constitution might be drafted and 
discussed at the next national party congress in 1990 
the constitution adopted in 1974 under josip broz tito created 
a loose confederation many see it as a main cause of the problems 
now because it leaves central power weak 
