nasa officials are discussing possibly installing 
us scientific instruments on a soviet spacecraft as part of a 
joint superpower project to monitor damage to the earths ozone 
layer tass said monday 
the soviet news agency quoted the head of a soviet delegation to 
recent superpower talks on space albert chernikov as saying the 
discussions in moscow dealt with the launching of a usmade 
spectrometer on the soviet meteor3 satellite in 199091 
in washington charles redmond a spokesman for the national 
aeronautics and space administration confirmed on monday that a 
nasa official is now in the soviet union for discussions on placing 
a spectrometer on a soviet satellite to monitor the ozone layer 
us equipment has been used aboard a soviet spacecraft in the 
past but redmond said this venture would be the first in which the 
united states would actually supervise its own equipment by working 
with the soviets 
tass said the goal of the joint program was to measure the 
earths ozone layer from space and calculate regional ozone 
depletion especially over antarctica 
the program has been worked out in accordance with the 
agreement reached at the sovietus summit in 1988 on expanding 
cooperation within the framework of the sovietamerican agreement 
on space exploration tass quoted chernikov as saying 
he said the project also would help implement the goals of the 
international vienna convention for protection of the ozone layer 
the next meeting of soviet and american specialists is scheduled 
for january in the united states tass said 
