a tropical storm off the south american coast 
reached hurricane force monday with winds of more than 80 mph as 
the system gathered strength over open water forecasters said 
hurricane joan the fifth hurricane of the atlantic season was 
upgraded from tropical storm status monday night and could 
intensify as it moves away from the colombian coast and into the 
western caribbean the national hurricane center reported 
the storms winds which had dropped to 45 mph sunday rose to 
at least 80 mph in an area northwest of the center and 75 mph winds 
over most of the system just above the minimum 74 mph hurricane 
level 
at 9 pm edt joans center was near latitude 119 north and 
longitude 741 west or just west of the guajira peninsula of 
colombia and 520 miles east of the island of san andres off the 
coast of nicaragua the hurricane was moving west at 10 mph and was 
expected to continue that motion through tuesday 
four to 8 inches of rain is forecast along joans path 
its a straight shot to costa rica and nicaragua but its not 
there yet there is no threat for the next 60 hours or so said 
center forecaster jim gross 
joan became the 10th named system of the 1988 atlantic hurricane 
season oct 11 when top winds passed the minimum 39 mph mark to 
qualify for classification as a tropical storm 
there have been four other hurricanes so far this season 
including hurricane gilbert which left more than 300 people dead 
and caused billions of dollars in damage as it tore through 
jamaica the cayman islands and mexicos yucatan peninsula 
the hurricane season extends from june 1 to nov 30 
