<TEXT>
the lights go up on carmen to reveal an 
extravagantly gaudy junkyard that owes as much to west side 
story as it does to the fiery passions of composer georges bizet 
another night sees giacomo puccinis tosca updated to the 
fascist rome of world war ii and performed on a tilted stage 
the two productions are the season openers at the english 
national opera a company that is making an international name for 
itself not only on the strength of its singing but for its 
imaginative stagings 
launched by lilian baylis as the sadlers wells opera in 1931 
the company moved to its present home the 2358seat london 
coliseum in 1968 it changed its name to the english national 
opera in 1974 and has since gathered a burgeoning reputation for 
productions that prize the work over individual stars and artistic 
vision over vanity vehicles 
we are a theater and not a museum music director mark elder 
said in an interview theater needs to be exploratory renewing 
inquisitive its not just a matter of doing the old classics 
in a sensationalistic way 
indeed not for although the eno has launched its 21st season at 
the coliseum with two warhorses tosca and carmen the 
breadth of its repertory also includes broadway musicals stephen 
sondheims pacific overtures and commissioned british works 
such as david blakes the plumbers gift 
nov 9 sees the european premiere of philip glass the making 
of the representative for planet 8 the american composers first 
work at the eno since akhnaten in 1985 in december eno mounts 
the first professional british staging of nikolai rimskykorsakovs 
1895 christmas eve in january the eno will have the british 
debut of aribert reimanns lear based on the shakespeare 
tragedy 
its the same eclectic mix of the tested and the untried that 
has wrought what nicholas kenyon in the new york times called a 
revolution in the standard of theater being offered to 
operagoers 
i take for granted that eno is the reference point of 
adventurous living music theater said peter jonas the 
companys artistic director 
opera took a long time to be accepted as essential in british 
life weve done a certain amount to help that 
the eno is responsible for 46 percent of the annual operatic 
activity in britain during its 10month 198889 season the 
company will present 204 performances of 18 operas in what jonas 
calls one of the heaviest repertory systems in the world 
production costs range from 33500 to 295000 the upper 
figure is about half the cost of the most expensive productions at 
the royal opera house covent garden the enos principal london 
rival 
in 1984 the company toured five american cities winning raves 
from houston to new york with works ranging from giuseppe verdis 
1851 rigoletto transplanted to new yorks little italy a 
century later to benjamin brittens patriotic 1953 gloriana 
the companys whitetieandtails version of the mikado was 
to be broadcast by pbs in late october in spring 1990 plans are 
in the works to perform a czech opera and kurt weills 1949 
street scene in the soviet union 
wherever the eno appears one constant remains it presents all 
foreignlanguage operas in english translations whether its 
prokofiev or puccini mozart or massenet 
what is missing is the texture of the original language 
said british soprano josephine barstow 
but barstow understands the policy even if she didnt always 
agree with it the fact that the eno always does perform in 
english is one reason why the audience has such a high level of 
concentration nowhere in the world have i personally encountered 
such concentration audiences come to listen and to think 
she said it proved useful to performers too 
its an enormous advantage to young singers to sing a major 
role like salome in their own language said barstow who first 
sang richard strauss vengeful heroine for the eno in 1975 its 
quite easy to learn opera in a language you speak reasonably well 
familiar works fuel the debate a new production of verdis la 
traviata won mixed reviews both for peculiarities of its staging 
and lapses in translation 
but earlier stagings in english of dmitri shostakovichs 
lesserknown lady macbeth of mtsensk and leos janaceks the 
makropolous case both starring barstow helped secure those 
operas exalted positions within the world repertory 
in november barstow travels to the san francisco opera to sing 
lady macbeth for the first time in russian which she might 
never have done had she not attempted it first in english 
ive tried out a lot of roles with the eno before ive done 
them elsewhere said barstow 
she is one of several singers who has reached international 
status through the eno others include thomas allen felicity lott 
and richard van allan 
in september she appeared as a soloist in beethovens ninth 
symphony under the boston symphony orchestra in 198990 she is 
scheduled to sing the marschallin in strauss der rosenkavalier 
at the houston grand opera 
peter jonas is pleased that alumniturnedstars more often than 
not return to their roots you do pinch yourself and think oh 
hes lost to us but quite a few come back in very favorable 
positions 
i suppose im one of the most loyal ones if you like said 
barstow who acknowledges the eno as home base 
its comforting to feel you belong somewhere in the whole big 
world of opera 
