<TEXT>
a 10 million lawsuit against the maker of a 
whooping cough vaccine that allegedly caused brain damage in an 
infant should go to trial the supreme court ruled monday 
the court without comment let stand a ruling in a virginia 
case that federal law does not foreclose such suits under state 
regulations that protect consumers against defectively designed 
products even if the federal government approves the products 
in other businessrelated cases the justices 
refused to hear an appeal by hallmark cards inc of an 
injunction barring it from selling greeting cards resembling those 
produced by blue mountain arts a small company in colorado 
agreed to consider allowing states to give larger retirement 
benefits to public employees forced to quit work before age 60 the 
case involves an ohio pension law provision that gave a 61yearold 
state employee lower disability retirement benefits than she would 
have gotten if she had been younger 
agreed to hear a reagan administration appeal aimed at making 
it easier for the government to conduct taxfraud investigations 
the justices said they will use a california case involving the 
church of scientology to settle a dispute over the power of the 
internal revenue service to obtain and use confidential documents 
the vaccine case involves tracy abbot who was 5 months old in 
august 1983 when she was inoculated with a vaccine called 
triimmunol manufactured by lederle laboratories a division of 
american cyanamid co 
her mother sued lederle in 1986 charging the vaccine caused 
brain damage in tracy and asking 10 million in damages 
triimmunol is a vaccine against diphtheria tetanus and 
whooping cough or pertussis and is administered to millions of 
children without serious side effects but it has caused serious 
injury in a small number of children 
the vaccine is approved by the federal food and drug 
administration and other government health agencies only one other 
company in the united states is licensed to produce a whooping 
cough vaccine 
whooping cough claimed thousands of lives before the vaccine was 
developed the most serious us epidemic was in 1934 when there 
were 265000 reported cases and 7500 deaths 
the abbot suit contends triimmunol is unreasonably 
dangerous and says lederle failed to develop a safer vaccine even 
though other forms of the vaccine have been used outside the united 
states 
a federal judge threw out the suit but the 4th us circuit 
court of appeals reinstated it in april 
the appeals court rejected arguments that the federal 
governments interest in promoting use of the vaccine would be 
frustrated by permitting suits alleging violation of state 
regulations federal law does not preempt such suits the appeals 
court said 
in a somewhat related issue the supreme court ruled in june 
that the government may be forced to pay damages when a vaccine it 
licenses causes the disease it was intended to prevent that case 
reinstated a suit in behalf of a boy who contracted polio after 
receiving a dose of federally approved vaccine 
the reagan administration has not announced a position on the 
abbot suit but the justice department has pointed out that 
alternative vaccines to the type lederle produces have not been 
proven safe and effective 
congress has passed a law which took full effect oct 1 
creating a fund to help compensate children injured by vaccines 
the new law places a tax on some vaccines to provide funds for 
injuries that occur from vaccinations after 1986 
</TEXT>
